{
  "doc_id": "31019",
  "text": "Sustaining AR after depletion of the acrosomal store AR is triggered by a massive entry of extracellular Ca 2+ induced by depletion of the acrosomal store [CITATION_1] . To explore whether Sr 2+ could replace Ca 2+ in the final massive entry, the previous requirement of store depletion was bypassed using TG. This Ca 2+ -ATPase-pump inhibitor induces acrosomal Ca 2+ release and the consequent influx of the extracellular ion required for AR [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Fig. 2) . A similar procedure was repeated using sperm incubated in TALP-Sr for 3 h. A significantly increased rate of AR was observed 30 min after addition of TG, reaching levels similar to those moved to Ca 2+ medium (Sr/Ca), or incubated under control conditions all the time (Ca) (Fig. 3) . To verify that the increase in AR observed after TG addition was sustained by the extracellular ion, treatment with TG was preceded by the addition of 1.8 mM EGTA. Chelation of the extracellular ion, either Ca 2+ or Sr 2+ , blocked the increase in AR induced by TG (Fig. 3) . Thimerosal was used as an alternative agent to induce the acrosomal store depletion [CITATION_5] , and similar results were obtained (data not shown). Taken together, these results suggest that once the acrosomal store is depleted, extracellular Sr 2+ can enter the cell and replace Ca 2+ in the final steps of the exocytotic process.",
